column12: wagtail
one: A single horizontal stroke, representing the number one.
cubes: In ancient scripts 丁 was written in two different ways: (1) depicting the walls of a city, which is now written as 圍, or (2) depicting a nail, which is now written as 釘.
axe handle: Pictograph of an axe handle.
seven: Depicts two lines crossing. Based on the original meaning "cut", now written as 切. The current meaning is a phonetic loan.
above: One stroke on top of another; variant of 上
under
kwukyel
ten thousand: Variant of 丏. Depicts a person (人) with a cover on top, conveying the original meaning "to not be seen". The current meaning is a phonetic loan. Simplified form of 萬.
unit of length ~ 3 meters: Depicts 10 (十) hand-lengths (又): 丈 (~3 meters) is a traditional Chinese unit of length equal to 10 尺 (~0.3 meters). The current use of 丈 as "husband" is a phonetic loan.
three: Three horizontal strokes, representing the number three.
up: Originally a small line or dot above a longer line, indicating "up". The vertical line was added to distinguish the character from 二 (two). Opposite of 下.
under: Originally a small line or dot below a longer line, indicating "down". The vertical line was added to distinguish the character from 二 (two). Opposite of 上.
table: Depicts a table.
no: Pictograph of sepals of a flower. The modern meaning "no" is a phonetic loan.
and: Simplified form of 與.  Phonosemantic compound. 舁 represents the meaning and 牙 represents the sound.  The traditional component 舁 was removed for simplification.
parapet: Depicts a person (人) with a cover on top, conveying the original meaning "to not be seen". The meaning later shifted to "invisible" and "parapet".
beggar: Depicts the blade of a knife. Similar in origin to 亡 and 方. Based on the original meaning "cut". The current meaning is a phonetic loan.

second earthly branch; (simp.) ugly: Depicts of a hand or paw with fingernails or claws. The current meaning is a phonetic loan. In simplified Chinese 丑 is also used to mean "ugly", while in traditional Chinese this meaning is written with a separate character 醜.
the period from 1 to 3 a.m.

monopolize: Depicts a hand (寸) spinning a wheel (叀). Based on the original meaning "turn", now written as 轉. The current meaning is a phonetic loan. The simplified character 专 was adapted from the cursive form of the traditional character 專.
moreover: Originally a pictograph of a sacrificial altar. The current meaning "moreover" is a phonetic loan.
great

generation: Origin unclear. Various explanations include (1) depicting three leaves on branches of a tree, a remnant from the top part of 枼 (leaf), which was phonetically similar in Old Chinese, (2) three dots added above the phonetically similar 止 (zhǐ - foot), or (3) three copies of 十 (ten), similar to the archaic character 卅 (thirty), depicting a 30-year generation.
thirty
hill: Pictograph of two hills.
third: Depicts a platform to put things on. The current meaning is a phonetic loan.

profession: Simplified character from the top 5 strokes of the traditional 業. Depicts a person (大) carrying a weapon (丵). Based on the original meaning "attack". The meaning later shifted to "expand territory" and "develop business".
bush: Simplified form of 叢. 从 represents the sound.
east: Pictograph of a basket or a bag. The current meaning "east" is a phonetic loan. The simplified character 东 was adapted from the cursive form of the traditional character 東.
silk, threads: Simplified form of 絲.  Duplication of 纟 (silk).
assist: Depicts two hands (廾) rescuing a person (卩) trapped in a pit (凵).
lose, discard: A horizontal line, depicting an item being discarded, added to the semantically similar character 去 (leave; go).
two
lose, discard: A horizontal line, depicting an item being discarded, added to the semantically similar character 去 (leave; go).
ancient form of the tenth of the twelve Terrestrial Branches
two: Simplified form of 兩.  Combination of two 丙 characters. 丙 also represents the sound.

strict: Simplified form of 嚴.  Phonosemantic compound. 喦 represents the meaning and 敢 represents the sound. Based on the original meaning "exaggerate". The meaning later shifted to "extreme", "severe", and "strict". The traditional component 敢 was removed for simplification.
side by side: Depits two people standing (立) side by side.
mourning: Simplified form of 喪. Depicts multiple mouths (口) wailing to mourn the death (亡). 桑 and 亡 represent the sound.
vertical line
[measure word]: Pictograph of one stalk of bamboo. Same as one half of the character for bamboo (竹).
forked: Pictograph of a fork or branch.
piece of wood: 丬 is a component form of 爿.

central: Depicts a flagpole. There is a circle in the middle marking the center of the flagpole. In older forms of the character, the flagpole  has streamers at the top and bottom used to show the direction of the wind
catch: Pictograph of a person with both hands outstretched.
luxuriant: Depicts a growing plant with leaves.
child's hairstyle bound in two tufts: Pictograph of a child's hairstyle with two tufts.
string: Pictograph of two objects on a skewer or strung together.
spit

draw near: Simplified form of 臨.  Depicts a person (人) looking (臣) down at a pile of objects (品). 品 also represents the sound. Based on the original meaning, "to look down". The meaning has shifted over time and now means "draw near".

chisel: Depicts a chisel-shaped tool or weapon. Related to 鑿 (chisel). Used in 對 to depict a tool to develop land, in 業 as a weapon to conquer territory, and in 菐 as an implement to pound something with.
dot: Depicts a dot.
eight
small round object: Pictograph of a person bent down and curled up. The meaning later shifted to "small round object" and "pellet, pill".
cinnabar (native HgS): Depicts a chunk of cinnabar found in a well for mining.
do: Simplified form of 為.  Pictograph of a hand (又) guiding an elephant (象) to do work (in ancient China elephants were tamed to do work). Based on the meaning "to work; to do".
master: Pictograph of a memorial tablet used for spiritual rituals, similar to 示.
bowl of food
beautiful: Simplified form of 麗.  Pictograph of a deer (鹿) with two beautiful antlers. The traditional component 鹿 was removed for simplification.
raise: Simplified form of 舉.  Phonosemantic compound. 手 represents the meaning and 與 represents the sound.
line: Line curving downwards to the left.
stretch
mow grass: Pictograph of a shears-like tool for cutting grass.
then: Possibly depicts a woman standing sideways with her breasts protruding. Based on the original meaning "breast", now written as 奶. The current meaning is a phonetic loan.

long time (ago): Depicts an arrow nock. The nock is the part of an arrow that is held against the bowstring before being launched. Based on the original meaning "arrow nock", now written as 氒. The current meaning is a phonetic loan.
to depend on: Origin unclear. Traditionally explained as a pictograph of a blade of grass.
[question particle]: Variant form of 幺, which is a pictograph of a twisted thread.

justice: Adapted from the cursive form of the traditional character 義. Phonosemantic compound. 羊 represents the meaning and 我 represents the sound. In ancient China sheep (羊) were associated with goodness and beauty, which is why 羊 is a component in characters like 美 (beautiful), 善 (benevolent), and 義 (justice).
kwukyel
[attributive particle]: Pictograph of a foot (止) going out of an area. The current meaning is a phonetic loan.
crow: Simplified form of 烏.  Pictograph of a crow. Similar to 鳥.
suddenly: Pictograph of a blade for cutting trees. Original form of 柞. The current meaning is a phonetic loan.
interrogative or exclamatory final particle: Depicts wind rustling through a tree branch (丂). Based on the original meaning "exhale, shout", now written as 呼. The current meaning is a phonetic loan.

lack: Line over 之 (foot), similar to how 正 (straight; correct) is a line over 止 (foot). Possibly represents the opposite of 正, since the top line in 乏 is written in the opposite direction as the top line in 正.
happy: Pictograph of an ancient wooden stringed musical instrument. The simplified character 乐 was adapted from the cursive form of the traditional character 樂.
people standing side-by-side: Depicts 3 people standing side-by-side. Ancient variant of 眾.
ping: Derived from 兵 (bīng), with one stroke removed. Symmetric with 乓, so that 乒乓 (pīngpāng) resembles the back-and-forth motion of ping-pong.
pong: Derived from 兵 (bīng), with one stroke removed. Symmetric with 乒, so that 乒乓 (pīngpāng) resembles the back-and-forth motion of ping-pong.
tall: Simplified form of 喬.  Originally written the same as 高 (tall). The top part of the character was altered to distinguish 喬 from 高.
tiger
rebel
ride
ride: Depicts a person (人) who has climbed up a tree (木).
second: Depicts a stream of water.
turning stroke: Variant of 乙.
kwukyel
to squint
nine: Depicts an elbow. Based on the original meaning "elbow", now written as 肘. The current meaning is a phonetic loan.
beg: Originally a variant of 气, which depicts a gust of air. The current meaning is a phonetic loan.
also: Depicts a child opening its mouth to cry. Original form of 嗁. The modern meaning is a phonetic loan.

practice: Simplified form of 習.  Phonosemantic compound. 彗 represents the sound and 日 represents the meaning. Based on the original meaning "to scorch". The current meaning is a phonetic loan. The traditional component 日 was removed for simplification.

hometown: Simplified form of 鄉.  Pictograph of two people facing each other, kneeling down to share a meal. Based on the original meaning "feast" or "offer food", now written as 饗. The meaning later shifted to "hometown". The right two components were removed for simplification.
lid
first character of Korean place name 'Halpho'
kwukyel
book: Simplified form of 書.  Phonosemantic compound. 聿 represents the meaning and 者 represents the sound. The simplified character 书 is derived from the cursive form of 書.
the beginning

used in Korean place names
rock
buy: Pictograph of money (貝) coming out of a netted bag (网). The simplified character 买 was adapted from the cursive form of the traditional character 買.
confusion, mess: Simplified form of 亂.  Depicts two hands (爪, 又) organizing tangled threads.
breast, milk: Depicts a mother holding (爫) a child (子) breastfeeding it.

finish: Pictograph of a young child, similar to 子, but without arms. Compare to 孑 (child only with right arm) and 孓 (child only with left arm). The current meaning is a phonetic loan.
kwukyel (old Korean hanja-based script) for “hammer”
give: Embellishment of the phonetically similar character 呂.
strife, quarrel: Simplified form of 爭.  Depicts two hands (爫 又) grabbing the same plow.
affair

matter: The characters 史 (history), 吏 (government official), 使 (cause; use; instruct), and 事 (matter; work; affair) are all etymologically related and all derive from the same ancient character, depicting a hand (又) holding a container for writing utensils. 事 and 史 were originally written the same, but later an extra mark was added to distinguish them.
two: Two horizontal strokes, representing the number two.
to take small steps
at: Pictograph of a musical wind instrument with a reed, which is now written as 竽. The current meaning is a phonetic loan.
deficit, lose: Originally the same character as 于, depicting a musical wind instrument with a reed, which is now written as 竽. The current meaning is a phonetic loan.
clouds: Depicts a swirl of clouds up (上) in the sky.
mutual: Depicts two symmetric figures intertwining with each other.
(archaic form) his
five: Origin unclear. Originally an X-shape.
well: Pictograph of the opening of a water well.
four: Four horizontal strokes, representing the number four.
turn around, turn back: Originally written the same as 回 (return). Later lines were added above and below to distinguish the two characters.
extend across, constant: Depicts the moon (月) between the earth and the sky。
Asia: Simplified form of 亞.  Depicts a wooden structure where coffins are placed. Based on the original meaning "tomb". The current meaning "Asia" is a phonetic loan.
a few
Asia
even
Asia: Depicts a wooden structure where coffins are placed. Based on the original meaning "tomb". The current meaning "Asia" is a phonetic loan.

urgently: Originally a pictograph of a person with lines at the top and bottom, depicting the original meaning "extremity". Later the 口 (mouth) and 又 (hand) components were added to depict shouting in an urgent situation, such as being chased.
head
death: Depicts the tip of a knife blade (刀). Similar in origin to 方. Based on the original meaning "tip of a blade", now written as 芒. The current meaning is a phonetic loan.
high: Pictograph of a person with a line through their legs. Original meaning unclear.
to cross: Pictograph of a person standing with crossed legs, conveying the meaning "to cross".
12th terrestrial branch: Depicts roots of a plant. Based on the original meaning "roots", now written as 荄. The current meaning is a phonetic loan.
also: Pictograph of a person, with two dots at the armpits. Based on the original meaning "armpit", now written as 腋. The current meaning is a phonetic loan.
give birth: Simplified form of 產.  Phonosemantic compound. 生 represents the meaning and 彥 represents the sound. The traditional component 生 was removed for simplification.
smoothly
Chinese land measure
kwukyel
enjoy: Originally a pictograph of a temple or a shrine. The meaning later shifted to "food offering" and "enjoy".
capital city: Pictograph of a tall building. Similar to 高. Based on the original meaning "high place". The meaning of this character has shifted over time and now means "capital city".
pavilion: Phonosemantic compound. 京 represents the meaning and 丁 represents the sound.
bright: Phonosemantic compound. 人 represents the meaning and 京 represents the sound. Depicts a person (人) in a high place (京).
to receive: Variant of 享. Originally a pictograph of a temple or a shrine. The meaning later shifted to "food offering" and "enjoy".

relatives: Phonosemantic compound. 木 represents the meaning and 辛 represents the sound. Based on the original meaning "chestnut". This character was repurposed during character simplification as the simplified form of 親.

slight: Hands grasping 执 and tearing apart a dress 衣

hundred million: Phonosemantic compound. 亻 represents the meaning and 乙 represents the sound. Simplified form of 億. Based on the original meaning "quiet; at rest". The current meaning is a phonetic loan.
what: The character is based on the original meaning "file of ten soldiers". The modern meaning "what" is a phonetic loan.
humaneness: Depicts a kind relationship between two (二) people (亻). 亻 also represents the sound.
surplus or excess
lonely: Phonosemantic compound. 亻 represents the meaning and 丁 represents the sound.
slanting: 厂 represents a slanted cliff and 夨 represents a person with a tilted head, thus conveying the meaning "slanting".
only: Simplified from 僅. Phonosemantic compound. 亻 represents the meaning and 堇 represents the sound.
to fall forward: Phonosemantic compound. 亻 represents the meaning and 卜 represents the sound. Simplified form of 僕.
enemy: Phonosemantic compound. 亻 represents the meaning and 九 represents the sound.
surname of the mother of Mencius
now: Depicts a closed mouth. Upside-down 曰. The meaning "now" is a phonetic loan.
to lie between: Depicts a person between two lines.

yet: Phonosemantic compound. 亻 represents the meaning and 乃 represents the sound.
from: Pictograph of one person following another.

cycle: Originally depicted farmland. The meaning later shifted to "circumference" and "cycle". Later the 口 component was added when 周 was used to refer to a geographical region to indicate that the character was only "mouthed", i.e. used for its sound. In simplified Chinese 周 is also used to mean "week", while in traditional Chinese this meaning is written with a separate character 週.

curse: Variant of 咒. Derived from 祝, with the 礻 (show) component being replaced by 口 (mouth) component when the meaning extended to "curse". Depicts a kneeling person (卩) opening their mouth (口) to pray for disaster to happen on someone.
